name: 4,5,6,7-tetrachloro-2-phenyl-1,3-benzodioxole
source: Karthikeyan M.; Glen R.C.; Bender A. General melting point prediction based on a diverse compound dataset and artificial neural networks. J. Chem. Inf. Model.; 2005; 45(3); 581-1978
Reason: Given the compound 4,5,6,7-tetrachloro-2-phenyl-1,3-benzodioxole, we can analyze the contribution of its different functional groups and structural elements to predict the melting point. Starting with benzene, which has a melting point of 5.5°C, we assess the following effects: - Cl substituents: Each chlorine substituent on an aromatic ring increases the melting point due to the added mass and the polar nature of the Cl. Chlorine atoms also engage in dipole-dipole interactions, which stabilize the solid form. There are four chlorines on one ring, so this effect is significant. - The dioxole ring (1,3-benzodioxole) introduces an additional heterocyclic system which increases rigidity and potential for π-π stacking. - The phenyl group attached to the dioxole ring contributes to the overall increase in molecular complexity and size, resulting in higher melting point due to increased intermolecular forces, particularly π-π stacking. From these considerations, the chlorines could increase the melting point by approximately 20-30°C each, as chlorinated aromatics generally have much higher melting points. The dioxole system could potentially add about 10-15°C. The additional phenyl group might contribute 5-10°C. Hence, the predicted melting point could be calculated as follows: Base benzene value: 5.5 Adding four chlorines: 4 x 25 (average of 20-30°C) = 100 Adding dioxole contribution: 15 Adding phenyl group contribution: 7.5 Prediction: 5.5 (base) + 100 (chlorines) + 15 (dioxole) + 7.5 (phenyl) = 128°C
